## 4. Module-by-Module Breakdown

### 4.1 Core — ML Engine (YOLOv8)
**File:** [core/ml_engine.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/ml_engine.py)

The [MLEngine](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/ml_engine.py#5-45) class wraps the **YOLOv8s** (small) model from [Ultralytics](https://github.com/ultralytics/ultralytics). It is responsible for the first stage of the pipeline: detecting people in each video frame.

- **Model:** [yolov8s.pt](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/yolov8s.pt) — pre-trained on the COCO dataset.
- **Target class:** Class 0 (person) only — all other detections are discarded.
- **Output:** A list of bounding boxes [(x1, y1, x2, y2, confidence)](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/tests/test_distributed.py#51-55) for each detected person.
- **Padded Crop:** A helper method [get_padded_crop()](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/ml_engine.py#30-45) extracts the bounding box region from the frame with a configurable pixel padding, used to feed into the feature extractor.

```python
# Runs YOLOv8 on a frame, returns [detected_persons]
detections = self.ml_engine.process_frame(frame)
```

### 4.2 Core — Feature Extractor (ResNet-18)
**File:** [core/feature_extractor.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/feature_extractor.py)

The [FeatureExtractor](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/feature_extractor.py#8-60) converts a detected person's image crop into a compact, fixed-length **512-dimensional feature vector** (a "feature ghost"). This vector numerically encodes the person's appearance.

- **Backbone:** `ResNet-18`, pre-trained on ImageNet.
- **Modification:** The final fully-connected classification layer is **removed**, leaving the 512-D feature embedding layer as the output.
- **Normalization:** The output vector is **L2-normalized** to unit length, making it suitable for cosine similarity comparisons.
- **Preprocessing:** Standard ImageNet normalization is applied (resize → center crop → normalise).
- **Device:** Automatically uses GPU (CUDA) if available; falls back to CPU.

> [!NOTE]
> L2 normalization is critical. By ensuring all vectors have a length of 1.0, the cosine similarity between two vectors becomes simply their **dot product** — making matching extremely fast and computationally cheap.

### 4.3 Core — Re-ID Tracker (Cosine Similarity)
**File:** [core/tracker.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/tracker.py)

The [ReIDTracker](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/tracker.py#3-42) implements **Re-Identification**: given a new feature vector, find whether this person is already known in the memory cache.

- **Algorithm:** For each vector in memory, computes the dot product against the incoming vector (cosine similarity since both are L2-normalized).
- **Threshold:** A configurable `similarity_threshold` (default **0.85**) determines the minimum similarity required for a match.
- **Output:** Returns the best-matching `global_id` and its similarity score. Returns `None` if no match crosses the threshold.

```
similarity = vec1 · vec2   (dot product of L2-normalized vectors = cosine similarity)
```

### 4.4 Core — Feature Fusion Engine (EMA)
**File:** [core/fusion.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/fusion.py)

The [FeatureFusion](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/fusion.py#3-29) engine updates a stored identity's feature vector when it is seen again. Instead of replacing the old vector, it uses an **Exponential Moving Average (EMA)**, which smoothly blends old and new information.

```
fused = (1 - α) × existing + α × new
```

- **α (alpha) = 0.3** — Gives 70% weight to the existing stable representation and 30% to the new observation.
- After blending, the result is **re-normalized** to unit length to maintain the L2 property used by the tracker.
- This makes the system **robust to slight appearance changes** (lighting, pose) while retaining the core identity.

### 4.5 Core — LRU Memory Cache
**File:** [core/memory.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/memory.py)

The [LRUMemory](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/core/memory.py#4-50) is the node's local Re-ID database. It stores up to `max_size` (default: **100**) identities using a **Least Recently Used (LRU)** eviction policy.

- **Backing data structure:** Python's `collections.OrderedDict`, which maintains insertion order and supports `move_to_end()`.
- **Eviction:** When the cache is full, the **least recently accessed** identity is automatically removed to make room for new ones.
- **Thread safety:** All read/write operations are protected by a `threading.Lock()`.
- **Stores per identity:** The 512-D feature vector and a `last_seen` Unix timestamp.

### 4.6 Network — P2P Node
**File:** [network/p2p_node.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/p2p_node.py)

The [P2PNode](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/p2p_node.py#12-268) is the heart of the distributed system. It manages all networking concerns:

- **TCP Server:** A listening socket accepts connections from any peer. Each connection is handled in a dedicated daemon thread.
- **Length-Prefixed Framing:** Every message is prefixed with a 4-byte big-endian integer indicating the message length. This fully solves TCP fragmentation — messages are always received completely.
- **Passive Peer Discovery:** When a message arrives from an unknown sender, the node automatically adds them as a peer (using host/port in the payload header).
- **Lamport Clock:** The node maintains a logical clock ([lamport_clock](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/tests/test_distributed.py#9-44) integer). It increments on every **send** and applies `max(local, received) + 1` on every **receive**.
- **Queue Flush Loop:** A background thread ([_queue_flush_loop](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/p2p_node.py#189-243)) runs every second, attempting to flush per-peer message queues to connected peers. If a peer is down, the queue retains messages.
- **Election Integration:** If the current coordinator (leader) becomes unreachable, the [BullyElection](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/election.py#4-90) engine is automatically triggered.
- **UI Callback System:** All events (logs, clock updates, coordinator changes, queue status) are emitted to the UI via a non-blocking callback mechanism.

### 4.7 Network — Thread-Safe Message Queue (Store-and-Forward)
**File:** [network/message_queue.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/message_queue.py)

Each peer in the system has its own [ThreadSafeQueue](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/message_queue.py#4-33). This implements the **Store-and-Forward** routing pattern:

1. When intelligence is broadcast, it is **enqueued** per-peer immediately.
2. A background thread tries to **flush** the queue when the peer is reachable.
3. If delivery fails (peer offline), messages **remain in the queue** for the next attempt.

This makes the system **tolerant of transient network partitions** — messages are not lost just because a peer is temporarily unreachable.

### 4.8 Network — Vector Commitment (SHA-256 Security)
**File:** [network/security.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/security.py)

The [VectorCommitment](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/security.py#4-26) class provides **cryptographic data integrity** for all intelligence transmitted across the mesh.

- **Mechanism:** Before broadcasting, a SHA-256 hash is computed over the JSON representation of `{global_id, timestamp, feature_vector}`.
- **Verification:** When a node receives a payload, it recomputes the hash and compares it against the transmitted hash.
- **Tamper Detection:** Any modification to the feature vector or metadata during transit will cause hash mismatch, and the payload is **rejected** with a "Tampering detected!" log.

> [!WARNING]
> Without this mechanism, a malicious node could inject false identities or corrupt feature vectors, poisoning the shared Re-ID database across the entire mesh.

### 4.9 Network — Bully Election Algorithm
**File:** [network/election.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/election.py)

The [BullyElection](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/network/election.py#4-90) class implements the classic **Bully Algorithm** for distributed leader election. The leader (coordinator) node is responsible for coordinating the mesh — if it fails, a new one must be automatically elected.

**How it decides who leads:** The node with the **highest port number** wins (acts as a unique node ID proxy in this implementation).

**Protocol steps:**
1. **Node initiates** an election by sending `ELECTION` messages to all nodes with a **higher port**.
2. If **no higher node responds** within 3 seconds → the initiator **declares victory**.
3. A higher node receiving `ELECTION` replies with `OK` and **starts its own election**.
4. The winner broadcasts a `VICTORY` message to all peers.
5. All nodes update their [coordinator](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/ui/dashboard.py#150-152) field upon receiving `VICTORY`.

**Fault Tolerance:** If the coordinator's connection is lost (detected in the queue flush loop), a new election is automatically triggered.

### 4.10 UI — Nerve Center Dashboard
**File:** [ui/dashboard.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/ui/dashboard.py)

The [NerveCenterUI](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/ui/dashboard.py#8-163) is a modern desktop GUI built with **CustomTkinter** (a themed extension of Tkinter). It provides a real-time operational view of the node:

| Panel | Content |
|---|---|
| **Top Control Bar** | Add Peer (IP:Port input), Start Stimulus button |
| **Status Bar** | Live **Lamport Clock** counter (green), current **Coordinator** node (blue) |
| **Video Feed** | Real-time annotated camera frame with bounding boxes |
| **Re-ID Gallery** | Scrollable log of all successful identity matches with similarity score |
| **Activity Log** | Network events, errors, new identity discoveries |
| **Peer Queues Panel** | Per-peer queue depth, updated every second |

**Thread Safety:** All UI updates are submitted via a `queue.Queue` (the [ui_queue](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/ui/dashboard.py#26-37)) and processed on the main Tkinter thread every 50ms via `self.after(50, ...)`. This prevents cross-thread Tkinter access violations.

### 4.11 Data — Stimulus Loader
**File:** [data/stimulus_loader.py](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/data/stimulus_loader.py)

The [StimulusLoader](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/data/stimulus_loader.py#4-54) is a flexible input abstraction that handles three types of stimulus sources:

| Source Type | Example | Behaviour |
|---|---|---|
| **Integer / digit string** | `0`, `1`, `"0"` | Opens OpenCV `VideoCapture(0)` — live webcam |
| **Video file** | `data/sample.mp4` | Streams frames from MP4 |
| **Image directory** | `data/frames/` | Reads sorted JPG/PNG files one-by-one |

The [reset()](file:///c:/Users/kanha/Documents/GitHub/EdgeIntelligence/data/stimulus_loader.py#50-54) method allows the system to loop gracefully when the stimulus is exhausted (e.g., for video files and image directories).

